postcontent: The high level overview of this frame is it is designed as an 80% frame, and includes all the necessary end mill bits and drill bits, along with the Jig to assist completing your pistol project accurately. Most people use a drill press with a cross vise to mill out the product, many folks have drill presses sitting in their garages, or can find someone who has one available to borrow. The frame accepts Glock17  9mm slides, as well as the Glock 40 caliber slide. The Smith and Wesson 40cal slide is also compatible with the Sig357 barrel configuration, which essentially gives you 3 different calibers to choose from. Unlike the Glock, this frame includes a uniquely extended beaver-tail, and most notably a super tactical 1911 pistol grip rather than the standard Glock styled pistol grip. Even better, this pistol grip includes a built in flared magwell for speed loading. This feature will surely be a favorite among competition shooters who require speed and accuracy. Finally, the areas that need to be milled out to complete this project include:    The barrel bridge    The top rails of the receiver   The slide guide rails

title: For Sale:  Ithaca X-Caliber Pistols
postcontent: Though these pistols were advertised in the 1989 Ithaca catalogue as the model 20 in .22 caliber and the model 30 in .44 magnum, they were never actually sold. These should not be confused with the Sterling Arms X-Caliber pistols made in Lockport, NY. Ithaca manufactured the barrels for those pistols and are so marked. These pistols features a unique firing pin which detonates both rimfire and centerfire cartridges. From the information I garnered, and according to S.P. Fjestad, author of the "Blue Book of Gun Values", only about 300 units were ever produced. All units were released in .22 caliber and production ceased due to unsolvable production issues. The specimens shown are marked Ithaca, in New-in-Box condition and UNASSEMBLED as they came from the factory. The pistols were made in two variants, one with Williams iron sights and the other outfitted with a Weaver rail. My understanding is that the Weaver rail variant is rarer. Other features are 10" barrels, Goncalo Alves wood stocks, hardware, and all original serialized owner's manuals ans boxes. Purchaser will also receive an original 1989 Ithaca catalogue listing the pistols. Much rarer than the Ruger Hawkeye, This is an opportunity to at-once own both variants released from the Ithaca factory in pristine condition. A must-have for any collector of the Ithaca brand or colectors of single-shot handguns. Serious inquiries only. Purchaser assumes all shipping, handling and insurance costs.

title: For Sale:  Ruger Vaquero Birdshead Case Hardened
postcontent: Up for sale is an ultra rare Ruger single action...more on the rare part in a minute. This is a large frame (original Vaquero), not the current "New Vaquero" model. The large frame originals are capable of "Ruger only" loads. It's the blued model with Ruger's faux case hardened frame. The revolver exhibits a slight turn line on the cylinder from handling but has not been fired outside of the Ruger factory. The model number is 00511 and the catalog number is BNVBH-453. Now the backstory on the rare part....Ruger transitioned from the original Vaquero to the new Vaquero late 2004 early 2005 timeframe and stopped making the originals. Thus gun was made in April of 2010 (based on the spent shell casing that came with it from the factory), 5 years after the end of production and 5 years after Ruger stopped the faux case hardening on their blued single actions. Furthermore, the notorious Ruger warning label on the barrel was much smaller and on the underside of the barrel. Prior examples were larger and on the side of the barrel. After acquiring, I called Ruger to verify the manufacter date. Between that and the model/catalog number (which were unique to this particular gun), I was able to find out through a few searches this was one of Ruger's parts clean up releases that were only sold through Davidson's, and that there were likely less than 200 or so made. The late production alone makes it a Ruger collector's object of desire, but the barrel warning label variation puts it over the top. If interested, feel free to reply with your number. I'd be happy to text additional pictures, including the factory label showing model/catalog as well as the dated spent casing. Price is $500

title: For Sale:  U.S. Carbine Caliber 30 M1 Built by Wichester
postcontent:
There are two kinds of 30 Cal. carbines … . One that loses its value over time ( a commercially made rifle ), and one that is an investment….that is, it will at least HOLD its value, and likely INCREASE in value over time. ( a genuine U.S Carbine .Caliber 30 M1 rifle , made during WWII). You DO get what you pay for
As well as being an important part of the United States Military history, you can defend your home and family with it. It is also easy for anyone in the family to shoot…. Very controllable, with plenty of punch .  Just as important, you can find parts for it if something needs to be replaced ( not always true with a commercially made rifle ).   
The rifles that I have listed from my collection, are all investment quality USGI rifles .  You decide what will be best for you in the long run… This receiver was made by Underwood Elliot Fisher ( serial number 2404xxx ) during WWII and was sent to Winchester as part of the " lateral support " program. Evidence of this is the bevel marking of WTA.  This I believe that this rifle was assembled very late in the war as many parts are late war Winchester ( Cartouched W marked M2 stock, 4 rivet handguard , Hemphill rear adjustable sight, flip safety, M2 mag catch, and C marked front band.) The rifle is in excellent condition with most, if not all, parts being Winchester.NOT AN IMPORT . $1395.  Questions welcome. FFL to FFL outside Oklahoma.
